The Title will be "Solutions to the Heat-Diffusion Equation Modeled in Python"

This project focuses on the numerical solution of the one- and two-dimensional Heat Diffusion Equation, a  partial differential equation that models the evolution of temperature in a medium over time. The primary goal is to transform the continuous equation into a discrete form using finite difference methods and to simulate heat flow with initial and boundary conditions. The project aims to visualize the temperature evolution and to compare the results with with real world physics to test if the simulation is correct.

As for the methods I didn't know what was appropiate but I looked it up and the numerical methods that seem appropiate to use are the "Forward Time Centered Space (FTCS) method", the "Backward Time Centered Space (BTCS) method", and the Crank–Nicolson method. The FTCS method provides a simple explicit approach but requires careful attention to stability conditions, while the BTCS and Crank–Nicolson methods introduce implicit formulations that improve stability and accuracy at the cost of solving linear systems at each time step. By using three different methods we can compare the computational efficiency and terms of stability of these numerical methods to solve the HDE. The way this is different from how I did it in the past is that I solved the equations by hand and tried to plot the solutions to boundary problems given to me. Now I am explicitely solving the HDE using numerical methods.

The problems I plan to solve are:

The HDE for a Cartesian domain in 1D (a line) and 2D (a rectangle), for any arbitrary
boundary conditions and an initial temperature distribution

Solve the HDE for a 2D annular domain(A Disk Shape), with arbitrary boundary conditions and an initial
temperature distribution

Solve the HDE for any 2D space, with arbitrary boundary conditions over arbitrary boundaries and an initial temperature distribution

